M, ‘Laurentianus plut. li., 11. 10, Lagom. 64, mem- branaceus sec. undecimi, characteribus Langobardicis, form. 4’ (Classen). It should be noted that the Cluentius is the only speech of Cicero which this codex contains: the rest of it is made up of Varro's de linqua Latina and the Rhetorica ad Herennium. This may be taken as some evidence that the speech had been singled out for special attention.
